segments.text: You know, what brings our students here, what makes our reputation what it is.
But I think it would be the scholarship, a limited amount of research, and a certain amount to outstanding faculty, either as an incentive or an award or whatever.
I'm not years or better at that than I am, but I would not object to doing that if I had that opportunity.
Okay, last thing.
Aggie story or two.
Do you have a sad one, a poignant one, a true Aggie event?
And then a funny one, goofy one from your experience anywhere.
What are your favorite Aggie stories?
I guess maybe let's say that.
Well, I have one that's a shocker.
But I probably turn that thing off.
Let me tell you what.
One of the funny ones that I remember, and this has to do with Ed Cooper.
Ed Cooper was such a stickler for
signs that were proper, you know, and he didn't really care for any kind of handmade signs.
This was some years ago before we completely automated everything.
He went over to the Coliseum and they were paying fees over there.
and somebody had put a sign up on the door that just said, the doors were locked.
Couldn't get in there and all the signs said, computer broke.
And he came back to the office and he called me in there and he said, Lacey, he said, get that sign fixed.
Well, he really wanted any of our doing to do it, but we got over there and took care of it because that was a funny story.
Or go to the other extreme, a sad or a poignant one.
A sad but a good one?
Well, it can be good, yeah.
I know, but good in terms of, does it necessarily have to deal with my tenure in the office?
No, no, no, no.
Just relating to A&M somehow.
This goes back to my support of the Texas A&M adjunct.
I think that was a wonderful program and I wish that maybe we don't need it today because the students are so better educated now.
I taught for a summer out there between semesters here when I was in the math department.
As you well know, the adjunct was put out there.
This was one of General Rudder's projects that he got going with Kimball County, which is where Junction, Texas is located.
And of course the most famous story about that is the Barry Bryant trip out there when he took all the football players and what, three buses went out and one came back or whatever it is.
But a lot of students were sent out there in order to get the intense tutoring from faculty members that would help them become prepared for on campus in the fall.
And my tenure in teaching was like five years.
But this one student made it all worth my while and time.
A kid by the name of Tommy Reagan.
And he was from some little bitty small town between San Antonio
and go to Lareda, down in that general area.
And when we got Tommy at the adjunct, he could read 60 words a minute when he wanted to go to school.
And he took a math class under me.
And classes out there started at 7 o'clock in the morning and ran till like 2 in the afternoon.
As a faculty member out there, you lived on the post.
It was kind of like a military city.
And you were, when you weren't in class, you were in a room where there was a help session being administered.
And the students could come in from 7 in the morning until 10 at night.
Saturdays included.
The only day we had off was Thursday.
And Tommy was having a hard time.
But he was there all of the time.
All of the time.
All of the time.
And we actually, we being some of the other faculty out there, had to just make him go and do something besides stay in these help sessions as much as he did.
Kid made it, got out of there just barely, came to this campus.
Three years later, was in vet school.
and is now a very, very successful veterinarian and large holder of real estate in Central Texas.
Got a letter from his mother that was almost illegible.
But the gist of it was, Dear Mr. Lacey, I just want to thank you for helping Tommy.
I did not finish the second grade, and my husband did not ever go to school.
And I am a postal clerk in this little bitty town, and I'm sorry I cannot remember.
And the thing that you did for Tommy, we taught him how to use his hands, but you were able to teach him how to use his hands.
And all of my associations,
and education.
That one.
You know, that makes it work well.
Oh, yes, yes, yes.
That keeps you going.
Oh, yes.
That's splendid, isn't it?
The other, I have one other if you want to hear it.
Oh, yes.
I had to revoke one diploma while I was at Texas A&M.
This was a diploma that we had awarded.
The book's all checked out to be correct.
John Beckerman and I did it together.
This man came in my office and he said, Mr. Lacey, he said, I'm on the police force in a town in North Texas.
And he said, I have not been able to sleep for three years.
Well, what's your problem?
He said, well, you guys awarded me a diploma and I didn't learn it.
I said, really?
He said, yeah.
He told me the circumstance.
and I checked the records and what had happened was he had taken a chemistry course in another institution and had falsified the transcript as he came in here.
He needed qualitative analysis here but he took quantitative there and he changed it so Beckham had given him the credit over in transfer.
And he said, I just can't live with myself any longer.
And so we revoked him.
And two years later, he came back here and took that course, and we graduated.
So that made me feel real good.
And to finalize it, in all of my contacts, I had my students up there, and had to come to see me about problems.
I only had one that I never could or didn't feel like when he left there that I had anywhere near satisfied him.
He was still there.
Still better than he was when he came in.
I guess out of those numbers.
Yeah.
That's a good batting average.
That's a good batting average, yeah.
Let's quit with that.
That's great.
All right.
